      <p align="justify"><a name="linktarget"><b><font color="#FF0000">Link Target</font></b></a><br>
        With this option, you can specify how you want an ad's url to open. (Ex. 
        You want to open new window when anyone click on specified an, just put 
        "_blank" in this field. Or if you homepage contains frames, you can specify 
        a frame name in this field too.) </p>
      <p align="justify"><a name="dateend"><b><font color="#FF0000">Date End</font></b></a><br>
        With this option, you are allowing the advertiser to advertise on your 
        website with an expiration date. (Ex. You sell the advertising space with 
        an expiration date of 21 September 2020, when 21 September 2020 arrives, 
        the ad will expire, regardless of the number of clicks or views) </p>
      <p align="justify"><a name="clickexpire"><b><font color="#FF0000">Click 
        Expire</font></b></a><br>
        With this option, the advertiser purchases a certain number of clicks 
        on the ad, when a number of clicks on the advertisement has been reached, 
        the ad will expire. (Ex. An advertiser purchases 10,000 clicks, when the 
        advertisement has been clicked on for the 10,000th time, the advertisement 
        expires.) </p>
      <p align="justify"><a name="imp"><b><font color="#FF0000"># of Impression 
        Purchased</font></b></a><br>
        With this option, you are allowing the advertiser to basically purchase 
        the number of times an ad appears on your website. (Ex. When 10,000 impressions 
        are purchased on the index.asp page, when the index.asp page is viewed 
        for the 10,000th time, the ad expires, regardless if the user clicks on 
        the ad.) </p>
      <p align="justify"><a name="campaign"><b><font color="#FF0000">Campaign</font></b></a><br>
        This is a certain strategy (advertising campaign) that is used for a specific 
        target market. This can contain one ad or a series of ads. </p>
